The Tokyo subway system gives me intense joy 🌟- something I never thought I would utter about an underground train system: immaculately clean, precisely on time, 💯 SAFE, covering every inch of this vast city, and I even like their upholstery choices. Tokyo, please offer some pointers to other cities 🙌.

Nothing but gratitude for this glorious, juicy, messy and precious life.

This time last year my mom was taken from me, from us. It was a sunny midday as she walked in a crosswalk, a man tore through a stop sign and our souls and she was no longer here to love me and be loved by me. A heavy blanket of longing and emptiness fell upon me that day and I have learned to surrender to its suffocating weight. Grief is agonizing, unpredictable and boundless but it is also a soft whispering remembrance of her infinite, maternal love. We have all or will all experience grief but instead of sharing and sitting in its gravity together we try to confine its power to designated times and places. But grief has no rhythm, no perimeter and no code of conduct. It transforms you and becomes you. I will never stop missing her and never stop loving her. 

I have not felt able to share here until now but there is no service in solitude so if it would be helpful to anyone I will try to share bits of my journey over the last year and as I move forward, hand in hand with my loss and my grief.
